JOINING DATA WITH DPLYR: JOINING TABLES

The information for data analysis is not always confined in a data table. Often you’ll need to join multiple tables together, so that they can be analyzed in a combination.

5.1 The LEGO datasets

The LEGO dataset is about the construction toys known as LEGOs, which contains information about the sets, parts, themes, and colors that make up LEGO history. The dataset is spread across many tables.

Import the parts table in form of .rds file in 0_data:

sets <- readRDS("sets.rds") # contains one row for each of the 4977 LEGO sets

Examine the table:

head(sets)
##     set_num                                                      name year
## 1   700.3-1                                     Medium Gift Set (ABB) 1949
## 2 700.1.1-1                                  Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB) 1950
## 3 700.B.2-1               Single 1 x 2 x 3 Window without Glass (ABB) 1950
## 4   700.1-2                            Extra-Large Gift Set (Mursten) 1953
## 5   700.F-1 Automatic Binding Bricks - Small Brick Set (Lego Mursten) 1953
## 6  700.24-1                                  Individual 2 x 12 Bricks 1954
##   theme_id
## 1      365
## 2      371
## 3      371
## 4      366
## 5      371
## 6      371

We see theme_id is not useful on its own. The useful information for theme_id is in another table called themes. Import and examine this table:

themes <- readRDS("themes.rds")
head(themes) 
##   id           name parent_id
## 1  1        Technic        NA
## 2  2 Arctic Technic         1
## 3  3    Competition         1
## 4  4 Expert Builder         1
## 5  5          Model         1
## 6  6        Airport         5

The theme_id variable in sets table links to the id variable in the themes table. For any individual set, we could find a theme that matches it.

5.2 Inner-join

To see the theme that each set is associated with, we will need to join the two tables with the inner_join verb from dplyr package.

Load the dplyr package:

library(dplyr) 
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union

Use inner_join to join the table sets to the table themes:

sets %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("theme_id" = "id"))
## # A tibble: 4,977 x 6
##    set_num   name.x                            year theme_id name.y    parent_id
##    <chr>     <chr>                            <dbl>    <dbl> <chr>         <dbl>
##  1 700.3-1   Medium Gift Set (ABB)             1949      365 System           NA
##  2 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)          1950      371 Suppleme~       365
##  3 700.B.2-1 Single 1 x 2 x 3 Window without~  1950      371 Suppleme~       365
##  4 700.1-2   Extra-Large Gift Set (Mursten)    1953      366 Basic Set       365
##  5 700.F-1   Automatic Binding Bricks - Smal~  1953      371 Suppleme~       365
##  6 700.24-1  Individual 2 x 12 Bricks          1954      371 Suppleme~       365
##  7 700.C.1-1 Individual 1 x 6 x 4 Panorama W~  1954      371 Suppleme~       365
##  8 700.C.4-1 Individual 1 x 4 x 3 Window (wi~  1954      371 Suppleme~       365
##  9 700.H-1   Individual 4 x 4 Corner Bricks    1954      371 Suppleme~       365
## 10 1200-1    LEGO Town Plan Board, Large Pla~  1955      372 Town Plan       365
## # ... with 4,967 more rows

The argument by tells how to match the tables: linking theme_id in the first table to id in second table.

The output shows a combined table which combines each set with its theme. But because both variables have a variable called name, the new combined table results in name.x and name.y.

Customize inner_join() so that it is more readable:

sets %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("theme_id" = "id"),
             suffix = c("_set", "_theme"))
## # A tibble: 4,977 x 6
##    set_num  name_set                          year theme_id name_theme parent_id
##    <chr>    <chr>                            <dbl>    <dbl> <chr>          <dbl>
##  1 700.3-1  Medium Gift Set (ABB)             1949      365 System            NA
##  2 700.1.1~ Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)          1950      371 Supplemen~       365
##  3 700.B.2~ Single 1 x 2 x 3 Window without~  1950      371 Supplemen~       365
##  4 700.1-2  Extra-Large Gift Set (Mursten)    1953      366 Basic Set        365
##  5 700.F-1  Automatic Binding Bricks - Smal~  1953      371 Supplemen~       365
##  6 700.24-1 Individual 2 x 12 Bricks          1954      371 Supplemen~       365
##  7 700.C.1~ Individual 1 x 6 x 4 Panorama W~  1954      371 Supplemen~       365
##  8 700.C.4~ Individual 1 x 4 x 3 Window (wi~  1954      371 Supplemen~       365
##  9 700.H-1  Individual 4 x 4 Corner Bricks    1954      371 Supplemen~       365
## 10 1200-1   LEGO Town Plan Board, Large Pla~  1955      372 Town Plan        365
## # ... with 4,967 more rows

Now we can answer interesting questions about the data. For example, find out the most common theme in LEGO:

sets %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("theme_id" = "id"),
             suffix = c("_set", "_theme")) %>%
  count(name_theme, sort = TRUE)

The part_cat_id variable in parts table links to the id variable in the part_categories table. Join two tables and add a suffix to distinguish the names:

parts %>%
  inner_join(part_categories, by = c("part_cat_id" = "id"),

5.3 Joining with a one-to-many relationship

Not all the tables have exactly the same observations like sets and themes, or parts and part_categories. Import and examine a new table, inventories:

inventories <- readRDS("inventories.rds")

An inventory represents a product that’s made up of some combination of parts.

head(inventories)
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
##      id version set_num 
##   <dbl>   <dbl> <chr>   
## 1     1       1 7922-1  
## 2     3       1 3931-1  
## 3     4       1 6942-1  
## 4    15       1 5158-1  
## 5    16       1 903-1   
## 6    17       1 850950-1

set_num variable suggests it links to the sets table. So we inner_join sets to inventories:

sets %>%
  inner_join(inventories, by = "set_num") # when the joining variables have the same name.
## # A tibble: 5,056 x 6
##    set_num   name                                    year theme_id    id version
##    <chr>     <chr>                                  <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
##  1 700.3-1   Medium Gift Set (ABB)                   1949      365 24197       1
##  2 700.3-1   Medium Gift Set (ABB)                   1949      365 24214       2
##  3 700.3-1   Medium Gift Set (ABB)                   1949      365 24215       3
##  4 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)                1950      371 11831       1
##  5 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)                1950      371 24230       2
##  6 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)                1950      371 24231       3
##  7 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)                1950      371 24232       4
##  8 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)                1950      371 24233       5
##  9 700.B.2-1 Single 1 x 2 x 3 Window without Glass~  1950      371   537       1
## 10 700.B.2-1 Single 1 x 2 x 3 Window without Glass~  1950      371 24240       2
## # ... with 5,046 more rows

The sets table starts with 4977 observations, but after joining now has 5056, because each set can have multiple versions, each of which gets its own inventory item. Filter this joined table for only the first version:

sets %>%
  inner_join(inventories, by = "set_num") %>%
  filter(version == 1) 
## # A tibble: 4,976 x 6
##    set_num   name                                    year theme_id    id version
##    <chr>     <chr>                                  <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
##  1 700.3-1   Medium Gift Set (ABB)                   1949      365 24197       1
##  2 700.1.1-1 Single 2 x 4 Brick (ABB)                1950      371 11831       1
##  3 700.B.2-1 Single 1 x 2 x 3 Window without Glass~  1950      371   537       1
##  4 700.1-2   Extra-Large Gift Set (Mursten)          1953      366 12985       1
##  5 700.F-1   Automatic Binding Bricks - Small Bric~  1953      371 11265       1
##  6 700.24-1  Individual 2 x 12 Bricks                1954      371  7645       1
##  7 700.C.1-1 Individual 1 x 6 x 4 Panorama Window ~  1954      371  3896       1
##  8 700.C.4-1 Individual 1 x 4 x 3 Window (with gla~  1954      371  3663       1
##  9 700.H-1   Individual 4 x 4 Corner Bricks          1954      371 15503       1
## 10 1200-1    LEGO Town Plan Board, Large Plastic     1955      372 10761       1
## # ... with 4,966 more rows

The result is a table with 4976 observations, compared to 4977 in sets table. This means there is one set that doesn’t have version 1, which is probably a data quality issue.

An inner_join keeps only an observation if it has an exact match between the first and the second tables. Paying attention to the number of rows before and after a join is an important part of understanding data.

Each LEGO piece has another attribute besides its part, its color, which are found in inventory_parts table.

This returns the same join, but the order of the tables is reversed. the columns will appear in a different order depending on which table comes first.

5.4 Joining three or more tables

Multiple tables could be joined using inner_join and pipe %>%

sets %>%
  inner_join(inventories, by = "set_num") %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("theme_id" = "id"), 
             suffix = c("_set","_theme"))
## # A tibble: 5,056 x 8
##    set_num  name_set            year theme_id    id version name_theme parent_id
##    <chr>    <chr>              <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl> <chr>          <dbl>
##  1 700.3-1  Medium Gift Set (~  1949      365 24197       1 System            NA
##  2 700.3-1  Medium Gift Set (~  1949      365 24214       2 System            NA
##  3 700.3-1  Medium Gift Set (~  1949      365 24215       3 System            NA
##  4 700.1.1~ Single 2 x 4 Bric~  1950      371 11831       1 Supplemen~       365
##  5 700.1.1~ Single 2 x 4 Bric~  1950      371 24230       2 Supplemen~       365
##  6 700.1.1~ Single 2 x 4 Bric~  1950      371 24231       3 Supplemen~       365
##  7 700.1.1~ Single 2 x 4 Bric~  1950      371 24232       4 Supplemen~       365
##  8 700.1.1~ Single 2 x 4 Bric~  1950      371 24233       5 Supplemen~       365
##  9 700.B.2~ Single 1 x 2 x 3 ~  1950      371   537       1 Supplemen~       365
## 10 700.B.2~ Single 1 x 2 x 3 ~  1950      371 24240       2 Supplemen~       365
## # ... with 5,046 more rows

In a series of joins, each will usually has different by arguments, and often they will have different suffix arguments, depending on the details of the tables you are joining.

Now connect sets, a table that tells us about each LEGO kit, with inventories, a table that tells us the specific version of a given set, and finally to inventory_parts, a table which tells us how many of each part is available in each LEGO kit, and colors.

This will let us answer question like “what are the most common colors of parts in LEGO sets?”

sets %>%
  inner_join(inventories, by = "set_num") %>%
  inner_join(inventory_parts, by = c("id" = "inventory_id")) %>%
  inner_join(colors, by = c("color_id" = "id"), suffix = c("_set", "_color")) %>%
  count(name_color, sort = TRUE)
## # A tibble: 134 x 2
##    name_color            n
##    <chr>             <int>
##  1 Black             48068
##  2 White             30105
##  3 Light Bluish Gray 26024
##  4 Red               21602
##  5 Dark Bluish Gray  19948
##  6 Yellow            17088
##  7 Blue              12980
##  8 Light Gray         8632
##  9 Reddish Brown      6960
## 10 Tan                6664

You will also get accustomed to working with data that spans a large number of tables.
